<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-s01e02" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Episode 2: Multiplication and Division</title>
  <assemblage>
    <title>Episode 2 Learning Goals</title>
    <p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
              Describe the physical action represented by multiplication and division.   
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
              Interpret the words used to indicate multiplication and division.    
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
              Interpret the symbols used to indicate multiplication and division.  
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
              Perform multiplication and division in real-world contexts.   
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    </p>
  </assemblage>
  <assemblage>
    <title>Episode 2 Key Terminology</title>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Product
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Quotient
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
  </assemblage>
  <assemblage>
    <title>Key Symbols</title>
    <p>
        Multiplication
        <md>
            * \hspace{1.0in} \text{as in}\,\, 5*2
        </md>
        <md>
            \times \hspace{1.0in} \text{as in}\,\, 5\times 2
        </md>
        <md>
            \cdot \hspace{1.0in} \text{as in}\,\, 5\cdot 2
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        Division
        <md>
            / \hspace{1.0in} \text{as in} \,\, 16/8
        </md>
        <md>
            \div \hspace{1.0in} \text{as in} \,\, 12\div 4
        </md>
        
    </p>
  </assemblage>
  <definition xml:id="def-multiplication">
    <statement>
        <p>
          <term>Multiplication</term> is the operation that corresponds to adding a number to itself repeatedly.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
   Multiplication can be represented symbolically in many ways:
   <md>
    3\times 2
   </md>
   <md>
    3\cdot 2
   </md>
   <md>
    3*2
   </md>
   <md>
    3(2)
   </md>
   <md>
   (3)(2)
   </md>
    All of these are read aloud as “3 times 2,” and all of them mean, “add 3 copies of 2 together.”
    <md>
        3\times 2 = 2+ 2+ 2 = 6
    </md>
    
  </p>
  <example>
    <p>
        Calculate <m>2\times 5</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Solution: This is asking us to add together 2 copies of 5. 
        <md>
            2\times 5 = 5 + 5 = 10
        </md>
        
    </p>
  </example>
  <example>
    <p>
        If you have 4 bags of apples, and each bag contains 3 apples, how many apples do you have in total? 
    </p>
    <p>
        Solution: Since we have several piles, each containing the same number of apples, this is a multiplication problem, specifically the problem
        <md>
            4\times 3
        </md>
        So, in total we have
        <md>
            4\times 3 = 3+ 3+3+3 = 12 \,\,\text{apples}
        </md>
        
    </p>
  </example>
  <assemblage>
    <title>Notice Something Neat</title>
    <p>
        You can change the order of the numbers in a multiplication problem and still get the same answer!
        </p>
        <p>
             <m>4\times 2 = 8</m> because 🟢🟢 + 🟢🟢 + 🟢🟢 + 🟢🟢 = 🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>2\times 4 = 8</m> because 🟢🟢🟢🟢 + 🟢🟢🟢🟢 = 🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢
        </p>
  </assemblage>
  <p>
    For problems involving larger numbers, you can use the <m>\times</m> button on your calculator to perform multiplication.
  </p>
  <example>
    <p>
        You get paid $2562 every month. How much are you paid in total in 6 months? 
    </p>
    <p>
        Solution: Since you’re adding up multiple copies of 2562, this is a multiplication problem, specifically the problem
        <md>
            6\times 2562
        </md>
        We can use the <m>\times</m> button on our calculator to find the answer to this problem:
        <md>
            6\times 2562 = 15,372
        </md>
        So that means we are paid $15,372 in total.
    </p>
  </example>
  <p>
    There are a couple of common key words that indicate that we need to perform multiplication. These include:
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                Double (multiply by specifically 2)
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Triple (multiply by specifically 3)
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Product
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Of
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  <example>
    <p>
        What is the product of 5 and 9?
    </p>
    <p>
        Solution: This is asking us to multiply 5 and 9.
        <md>
            5\times 9 = 45
        </md>
        
        </p>
  </example>

  <example>
    <p>
        What results when we double the number 8?
    </p>
    <p>
      This is asking us to multiply 8 by 2.
      <md>
        2\times 8 = 16
      </md>
        
    </p>
  </example>

  <definition xml:id="def-division">
    <statement>
        <p>
          <term>Division</term> is the operation that corresponds to splitting a pile into smaller piles. 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    Division can be represented symbolically in many ways:
    <md>
        8 \div 2
    </md>
    <md>
        8/2
    </md>
    <md>
    \frac{8}{2}
    </md>
    All of these are read aloud as “8 divided by 2.”
  </p>
  <p>
    There are two ways to think about 8 divided by 2:
    <ol marker="A)">
        <li>
            <p>
                Take a pile containing 8 items and split that into 2 smaller piles. Then count the number of objects in each pile you made.
            </p>
            <p>
              🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢  →  🟢🟢🟢🟢 and 🟢🟢🟢🟢  
            </p>
            <p>
             There are 4 items in each pile, so <m>8\div 2 = 4</m>
   
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
               Take a pile containing 8 items and split that into piles so that each pile contains 2 items. Then count the number of piles you made. 
            </p>
            <p>
               🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢  →  🟢🟢 and 🟢🟢 and 🟢🟢 and 🟢🟢 
            </p>
            <p>
                We made 4 piles, so <m>8\div 2 =4</m>
            </p>
        </li>
        </ol>
  </p>
  <example>
    <p>
       If you have 6 cookies, and those cookies need to be shared fairly between 3 people, how many cookies can each person eat? 
    </p>
    <p>
        Solution: Since we are splitting a pile of 6 cookies into 3 smaller piles, this is a division problem. Specifically, this is the problem:
        <md>\frac{6}{3}</md>
        Because 🍪🍪🍪🍪🍪🍪 → 🍪🍪 and 🍪🍪 and 🍪🍪 we see that each person gets 2 cookies. In other words,
        <md>\frac{6}{3}=2</md>
    </p>
      </example>

      <example>
        <p>
            You are throwing an all-day party and you have 12 sodas. Each party guest is expected to drink 3 sodas. How many guests can you invite to the party?
        </p>
        <p>
            Solution: Since we are splitting a pile of 12 sodas into portions, each containing 3 sodas, this is a division problem. Specifically, this is the problem:
            <md>\frac{12}{3}</md>
            Because 🥤🥤🥤🥤🥤🥤🥤🥤🥤🥤🥤🥤 → 🥤🥤🥤and 🥤🥤🥤 and 🥤🥤🥤 and 🥤🥤🥤 we see that we can give sodas to 4 guests. In other words,
            <md>\frac{12}{3}=4</md>
        </p>
      </example>

      <assemblage>
        <title>Notice Something Neat</title>
        <p>
            When you divide 0 by any other number, the result is always 0.
            <md>\frac{0}{3}=0 </md>
            Because if you have 0 items split into 3 piles, each pile will also contain 0 items!
        </p>
      </assemblage>

      <p>
        For problems involving larger numbers, you can use the / button or the <m>\div</m> button on your calculator to perform multiplication.
      </p>

      <example>
        <p>
           A school is organizing a field trip. There are 168 students going on the trip. Each bus can carry 24 students. How many buses are needed to transport all the students? 
        </p>
        <p>
            Solution: Since splitting 168 students into piles each containing 24 students, this is a division problem, specifically the problem
            <md>168\div 24</md>
            We can use the <m>\div </m> button on our calculator to find the answer to this problem:
            <md> 168\div 24=7</md>
            So that means we would need 7 buses in total.
        </p>
      </example>

      <p>
      There are a couple of common key words that indicate that we need to perform multiplication. These include:
      <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                Per
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Half (divide specifically by 2)
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Quotient
            </p>
        </li>
      </ul>  
      </p>
      <example>
        <p>
            What is half of 18?
        </p>
        <p>
            This is asking us to divide 18 by 2:
            <md>\frac{18}{2}=9</md>
        </p>
      </example>
      <example>
        <p>
            A car can drive 120 miles on 6 gallons of gas. What's the car's mileage in miles per gallon?
        </p>
        <p>
            Solution: This is asking us to divide 120 by 6:
            <md>\frac{120}{6}=20 </md>
        </p>
      </example>
      <xi:include href="ws-s01e02.ptx" />
  </section>